<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Brittain is a democracy in all name. The last times the Monarch refused to give assent to a bill was in ~1914<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
actually, up until a few years ago, Britian had hereditery peers in parliment.  Therefore, they were not a completely democratic country.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>It isn't a standard, it's a fact. Religion can destabilize a country or a region. Look at the middle east, it has the most theocratic governments, and is one of the least stable regions.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
<br>
Politics is a lot more to blame for the situation in the middle east.  Primarily due to world wide politics after world war 2 and the collapse of the british empire.  Interestingly enough, the governments of the middle east are more stable than most African or South American regions.  How do you explain this since these regions are not known for religeon based politics?  By the way, on related note, is Argentina ok to have nukes?  Democratically elected government with no religeous influence.  How about Mexico? <p><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="font-size:xx-small;"><br>
